const TOPIC_BOOKS = [
  {
    id: 1,
    title: "Relationships",
    scripture: "Bhagavad Gita",
    subtitle: "Simple wisdom from the Gita for love, heartbreak & bonding.",
    source: "Explore Bhagavad Gita",
    bg: "#7A5230",
    accent: "#F0C97A",
    emoji: "🌺",
    image: BOOK_IMAGES[1] || null,
    sampleVerse: "You have the right to perform your actions, but you are not entitled to the fruits of the actions. — BG 2.47",
    pages: [
      { heading: "Do Your Best, Let Go of the Rest", text: "BG 2.47 — 'You have the right to act, but not to the results.' In a relationship, you can love someone with all your heart. But you cannot control how they feel or what they do. So give your best love, then let go. Their choices are theirs. Your peace is yours. Stop keeping score." },
      { heading: "Stay Steady Through the Ups and Downs", text: "BG 2.48 — 'Do your duty with a calm mind. Do not cling to success or failure. Stay balanced.' Every relationship has good days and bad days. When they praise you, stay humble. When they upset you, stay calm. Real love does not change with the weather. Be the steady one." },
      { heading: "Stop Wanting, Start Loving", text: "BG 2.55 — 'When you drop all desires and feel complete within yourself, you have found true wisdom.' Most pain in love comes from wanting. 'I want them to text me.' 'I want them to change.' These wants make you suffer. Try this: just love without wanting anything back. See how free you feel." },
      { heading: "How to Stay Calm After a Breakup", text: "BG 2.56 — 'A wise person is not upset by hard times, does not chase happiness, and is free from fear, anger, and attachment.' After a breakup, your feelings will jump between anger and sadness, hope and hate. Do not fight them. Watch them like clouds passing by. You are the sky, not the storm." },
      { heading: "Love Without Holding On Too Tight", text: "BG 2.57 — 'The wise person does not cling to anything. They do not get too happy when things go well, nor too sad when things go wrong.' If you love someone, let them be free. Holding too tight only pushes them away. Love like the wind — you cannot see it, but you can feel it." },
      { heading: "How Small Wants Turn into Big Fights", text: "BG 2.62-63 — 'First you think about something. Then you want it. If you do not get it, you get angry. Anger clouds your mind. You forget what matters. And you end up hurt.' This is how most fights start. You wanted attention. They did not give it. You got angry. Next time, catch it early. Step back before anger takes over." },
      { heading: "When Nothing Feels Good Anymore", text: "BG 2.59 — 'When you find something better, the old things stop tempting you.' After heartbreak, food, music, even your favorite shows feel empty. That emptiness is not a curse. It is a sign that your soul wants something deeper. Sit with the silence. You will find a new kind of peace there." },
      { heading: "This Pain Will Pass", text: "BG 2.14 — 'Pleasure and pain come and go like the seasons. They are temporary. Learn to handle them with patience.' The love you lost hurt because it was real. But this pain is not permanent. It will fade. You have survived every hard day so far. You will survive this one too. Give it time." },
      { heading: "Be Kind Without Expecting a Thank You", text: "BG 3.19 — 'Do your duty without clinging to the results. When you work without attachment, you find true freedom.' Be a good partner because that is who you are, not because they will notice or thank you. Cook for them. Support them. Listen to them. Not for a reward, but because love is something you do, not something you trade." },
      { heading: "Be the Love You Want to See", text: "BG 3.21 — 'Whatever great people do, others follow. The standards they set become an example.' You cannot force someone to treat you well. But when you are kind, honest, and respectful, you show them how you want to be treated. Your actions teach more than your words ever could." },
      { heading: "Stop Asking for Applause", text: "BG 4.20 — 'Let go of attachment to results. Be happy and independent. Do what you do because it is right, not for a reward.' Think about how many fights happen because you felt unappreciated. 'I did so much and they did not even say thank you.' Let that go. Your worth does not come from their thanks." },
      { heading: "See the Same Spark in Everyone", text: "BG 5.18 — 'Wise people see the same soul in a priest, a cow, an elephant, a dog, and even a person who eats dogs.' The person who broke your heart is still a soul on a journey, just like you. When you can see the good in them, even after they hurt you, you will find real freedom." },
      { heading: "Love Yourself First", text: "BG 6.5 — 'Lift yourself up with your own effort. Do not put yourself down. You are your own best friend, or your own worst enemy.' Before you can truly love someone else, you need to love yourself. Stop begging for love from people who do not value you. You are not an option. You are a priority — at least to yourself." },
      { heading: "Your Mind Will Play Tricks on You", text: "BG 6.6 — 'If you control your mind, it becomes your best friend. If you do not, it becomes your worst enemy.' After a breakup, your mind will replay everything. 'What if I said this? What if I did that?' That voice is lying to you. You are not your thoughts. Watch them come and go. Do not believe everything you think." },
      { heading: "Put Yourself in Their Shoes", text: "BG 6.32 — 'The best person is one who sees the joy and pain of others as their own.' Before you get angry at someone, pause. Ask yourself: what are they going through right now? Maybe they are tired. Maybe they are hurt too. When you try to feel what they feel, fights turn into understanding." },
      { heading: "Even the One Who Rejected You Is Divine", text: "BG 9.29 — 'I am the same to all beings. No one is special to Me and no one is hated by Me.' Even someone who left you still has a spark of the divine in them. You do not have to be friends with them. But you can still wish them well. That is how you heal without holding bitterness." },
      { heading: "Let Go and Let God", text: "BG 9.34 — 'Fix your mind on Me. Give your heart to Me. Offer everything to Me. Surrender to Me.' When a relationship ends, stop asking 'why did this happen?' Start asking 'what is this teaching me?' Trust that life has a plan bigger than your understanding. Let go. Something better is waiting." },
      { heading: "When You Feel Lost, Sit in Silence", text: "BG 10.10 — 'To those who love Me and serve Me, I give the wisdom to find their way back to Me.' If you are confused after a breakup, do not look for answers in your phone or in their social media. Sit quietly. Meditate. Breathe. The answer is already inside you. Trust the silence." },
      { heading: "No One Can Complete You", text: "BG 11.55 — 'Do all your work for Me. Keep Me as your goal. Be free from attachment. Do not hate anyone.' Love your partner with all your heart. But remember: no human can fill the hole in your soul. That void is for the divine. When you stop expecting another person to complete you, you finally become whole." },
      { heading: "Be Someone Easy to Love", text: "BG 12.13-14 — 'A person who is kind to everyone, friendly, caring, not selfish, patient, and forgiving — such a person is very dear to Me.' Read that again. These are the qualities of a person everyone wants to be with. Be this person. Not for them. For yourself. The love you give yourself sets the standard for the love you attract." },
      { heading: "Do Not Disturb the Peace", text: "BG 12.15 — 'The person who does not disturb others and is not disturbed by others is very dear to Me.' Before you say something harsh, ask: will this make things better or worse? Before you react with anger, ask: am I letting this person steal my peace? Be the calm one. It is a superpower." },
      { heading: "The Real Ingredients of Love", text: "BG 13.8-12 — 'Humility, honesty, kindness, forgiveness, self-control, and simple living — these are true wisdom.' Check yourself against this list. Are you humble enough to say sorry? Are you honest enough to speak the truth with love? Do you have self-control when you are angry? Real love is built on these simple things." },
      { heading: "See the Soul, Not the Mistake", text: "BG 13.28 — 'One who sees the same God living in all beings sees the truth.' The person who hurt you is more than their worst moment. They have a soul. They are learning, just like you. When you can see the divine in someone who broke your heart, you stop seeing them as a villain. And that sets you free." },
      { heading: "Your Soul Is Eternal, Your Relationship Is Temporary", text: "BG 15.7 — 'Every living being is a part of Me.' You are an eternal soul having a human experience. Every relationship is a meeting of two souls in a temporary world. That is why it hurts so much when it ends — your soul knows how deep the love was. But trust that true soul connections never really disappear." },
      { heading: "Build These Qualities in Yourself", text: "BG 16.1-3 — 'Fearlessness, a clean heart, helping others, self-control, honesty, non-violence, truthfulness, calmness, compassion, gentleness, and modesty.' This is the Gita's guide to being a good human being and a good partner. Pick one quality from this list that you need most today. Work on it. That is how you grow." },
      { heading: "Know When to Walk Away", text: "BG 18.66 — 'Give up everything else and just come to Me. Do not be afraid. I will protect you.' Some relationships are not love — they are chains. If someone keeps hurting you, it is okay to leave. Walking away from toxic love is not failure. It is the bravest thing you can do. Choose yourself." },
      { heading: "Love That Never Dies", text: "BG 2.20 — 'The soul is never born and never dies. It cannot be killed, not even by fire or sword.' Real love is not about bodies or time. It is about souls. The love you shared with someone special will never truly die. It becomes a part of you. Carry it with gratitude, not grief." },
      { heading: "Stop Trying to Change Them", text: "BG 3.27 — 'People act according to their nature. The ego says, \"I am doing this,\" but that is an illusion.' You cannot change anyone. They will only change when they are ready. Your job is not to fix them — it is to work on yourself. Focus on your own growth. When you change, the world around you changes." },
      { heading: "React Less, Respond More", text: "BG 2.58 — 'A wise person pulls their senses back like a tortoise pulls its legs into its shell.' In the middle of a fight, the best thing you can do is stop. Count to ten. Take a breath. Walk away for a minute. Reacting makes things worse. Responding takes strength. Be the tortoise." },
      { heading: "Love Is a Verb, Not a Noun", text: "BG 3.8 — 'Do your duty. Action is better than doing nothing.' Love is not something you feel — it is something you do. It is making tea when they are tired. It is saying sorry first. It is showing up even when it is hard. Stop asking 'do they love me?' Start asking 'am I loving well today?'" },
      { heading: "You Are Complete, With or Without Them", text: "BG 6.18 — 'When the mind is calm and rests in the self, free from all desires, that is true peace.' You were whole before you met them. You will be whole after they leave. The love you are looking for outside is already inside you. Find it. Nurture it. Then share it from a full heart, not an empty one." },
      { heading: "Forgive for Your Own Peace", text: "BG 16.21 — 'There are three gates to hell: lust, anger, and greed. Run from them.' Holding a grudge is like drinking poison and hoping the other person dies. Forgive them — not because they deserve it, but because you deserve peace. Anger only hurts you. Let it go. Your heart will feel lighter." },
      { heading: "Trust the Universe", text: "BG 18.46 — 'By honoring the source of all life, you reach perfection.' You do not have to force anything. If a relationship is meant for you, it will find its way back. If it is not, something better is on its way. Trust that life knows what it is doing. Your only job is to keep growing." },
      { heading: "What You Give Comes Back", text: "BG 3.10 — 'In the beginning, God created people and said: help each other. Give freely. And you will receive.' Love is like a boomerang. When you give kindness, kindness comes back to you. Not always from the same person, not always right away. But it comes back. So keep being kind. Keep loving. The universe keeps track." },
      { heading: "Your Ex Was Your Teacher", text: "BG 4.34 — 'Learn from wise people. Ask questions. Serve them. They will guide you.' Every person who comes into your life has something to teach you. Ask yourself: what did this relationship teach me about myself? What wound did it show me? Thank them for the lesson and move on. The guru comes in many forms." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 2,
    title: "Life Lessons",
    scripture: "Chanakya Neeti",
    subtitle: "Practical life lessons from Chanakya for everyday living.",
    source: "Explore Chanakya Neeti",
    bg: "#4A5E38",
    accent: "#B8D4A0",
    emoji: "🦁",
    image: BOOK_IMAGES[2] || null,
    sampleVerse: "Education is the best friend. An educated person is respected everywhere. Education beats the beauty and the youth. — Chanakya Neeti 1.6",
    pages: [
      { heading: "Knowledge Is Your Best Friend", text: "CN 1.6 — 'Education is the best friend. An educated person is respected everywhere. Education beats beauty and youth.' Looks fade. Money comes and goes. But what you learn stays with you forever. Nobody can steal your knowledge. Invest in your mind — read, ask, explore. That friendship will never leave you." },
      { heading: "Ask Three Questions Before You Act", text: "CN 1.15 — 'Before you start some work, always ask yourself three questions — Why am I doing it, what the results might be, and will I be successful?' Most mistakes happen because we rush. Stop. Think. Ask yourself: is this worth it? What will happen after? Can I really do this? One minute of thinking can save you years of regret." },
      { heading: "Hard Work Always Wins", text: "CN 3.11 — 'There is no poverty for the industrious.' Chanakya says: a hardworking person never stays poor. You might not have money, contacts, or luck. But if you work hard every single day, you will find a way. The universe rewards effort, not excuses." },
      { heading: "Knowledge Without Practice Is Useless", text: "CN 4.15 — 'Knowledge without practice is like poison.' Reading a thousand books on swimming won't save you from drowning. You have to get in the water. Same with life. You can watch all the videos, read all the posts — but if you don't apply what you learn, it means nothing. Practice is what turns knowledge into power." },
      { heading: "Learn From Other People's Mistakes", text: "CN 5.15 — 'Learn from the mistakes of others. You cannot live long enough to make them all yourself.' Smart people don't have to touch fire to know it burns. They watch others get burned and learn. Your friend's bad relationship, your cousin's failed business — learn from them. Life is too short to make every mistake yourself." },
      { heading: "Choose Your Friends Carefully", text: "CN 1.4 — 'A foolish friend is more dangerous than an enemy.' The people you spend time with shape your future. If you hang out with lazy people, you will become lazy. If you sit with wise people, you grow. Choose your circle like your life depends on it — because it does." },
      { heading: "Test People Before You Trust Them", text: "CN 1.8 — 'Do not trust someone without reason. Test them first.' Chanakya says: trust is earned, not given. Before you share your secrets, your money, or your heart — watch how they behave when you have nothing to offer. Real friends show up when you are down, not just when you are winning." },
      { heading: "Don't Be Too Simple or Straight", text: "CN 7.12 — 'Do not be too straight in your dealings. In the forest, straight trees get cut first. The crooked ones stay standing.' Being honest is good. Being naive is dangerous. You don't have to be dishonest, but you need to be smart. The world will take advantage of you if you are too simple. Keep your eyes open." },
      { heading: "The Present Moment Is All You Have", text: "CN 8.5 — 'Do not fret about the past, nor be anxious about the future. Wise people deal only with the present moment.' The past is gone. The future is not here yet. All you have is right now. Stop replaying old hurts. Stop worrying about what might happen. Focus on what you can do today. This moment is your only power." },
      { heading: "Fear Must Be Attacked Immediately", text: "CN 15.1 — 'As soon as fear approaches, attack and destroy it.' Fear grows when you run from it. The longer you wait, the bigger it becomes. Whether it's asking someone out, starting a business, or having a hard conversation — do it before fear takes over. Strike first. Your courage will surprise you." },
      { heading: "A Book Is Useless If You Don't Read It", text: "CN 10.3 — 'Books are as useful to a stupid person as a mirror is to a blind person.' Owning books doesn't make you smart. Reading them does. Don't collect knowledge — consume it. A library full of unread books is just decoration. Open the book. The real value is on the inside." },
      { heading: "Keep Your Plans to Yourself", text: "CN 1.12 — 'Do not reveal what you have planned to anyone. Keep it secret and execute it with determination.' The moment you tell everyone your goal, you lose the energy to do it. Why? Because you already got the praise. Work in silence. Let your success make the noise. Show them the results, not the plan." },
      { heading: "Where You Live Matters", text: "CN 1.9 — 'Do not stay where there is no respect, no livelihood, no friends, and no chance to learn.' Your environment shapes your destiny. If your city, job, or relationship is draining you and giving nothing back — leave. You are not a tree. You can move. Find a place where you can grow." },
      { heading: "Friendship Between Equals Only", text: "CN 12.17 — 'Never make friends with people who are above or below you in status. Such friendships will never bring happiness.' Chanakya says real friendship needs equality. If one person feels superior or inferior, resentment builds. Find friends who are on your level — same values, same drive, same respect for each other." },
      { heading: "Your Tongue Can Build or Break", text: "CN 2.7 — 'The wound caused by words takes longer to heal than a wound caused by fire.' Be careful what you say. You can apologize for harsh words, but you cannot unsay them. Before you speak, ask: is this true? Is this kind? Is this needed? If not, stay silent. Your tongue is a double-edged sword." },
      { heading: "The Whole World Is a Classroom", text: "CN 4.6 — 'A wise person can learn from everything. The whole world is their teacher.' You don't need a guru to learn. Watch nature — it teaches patience. Watch children — they teach wonder. Watch your enemies — they teach you your weaknesses. Stay open. Everyone and everything has a lesson for you." },
      { heading: "Purity of Heart Over Rituals", text: "CN 13.4 — 'Purity of mind and heart is more important than bathing in holy rivers.' You can go to temples, chant prayers, follow rituals — but if your heart is dirty with greed, anger, and jealousy, it means nothing. Clean your heart first. Be kind. Be honest. That is the real worship." },
      { heading: "Don't Let Success Go to Your Head", text: "CN 6.6 — 'A man is great not because he is wealthy, but because he has character.' Money and success can make you arrogant. But character keeps you grounded. Chanakya says: wealth is temporary, but who you are at your core stays forever. Stay humble. Remember where you came from." },
      { heading: "Serve Others While You Can", text: "CN 9.1 — 'As long as your body is healthy and death is distant, serve others. When death is near, what can you do?' Don't wait until you are old or rich to help people. Help now. Share what you have today. A small kindness done now is worth more than a big promise you never keep." },
      { heading: "You Arrive Alone and Leave Alone", text: "CN 8.1 — 'A man is born alone, dies alone, and experiences the results of his actions alone.' At the end of the day, your life is your responsibility. Your successes and failures are yours alone. Don't blame others. Don't depend on others for your happiness. Stand on your own feet. Your life is in your hands." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 3,
    title: "Anxiety & Stress",
    scripture: "Bhagavad Gita",
    subtitle: "Krishna's timeless wisdom to calm your anxious mind.",
    source: "Explore Bhagavad Gita",
    bg: "#3D5570",
    accent: "#9DC4D8",
    emoji: "🕊️",
    image: BOOK_IMAGES[3] || null,
    sampleVerse: "You have the right to perform your actions, but you are not entitled to the fruits of the actions. — BG 2.47",
    pages: [
      { heading: "Stop Worrying About Results", text: "BG 2.47 — 'You have the right to act, but not to the fruits of your actions.' Anxiety comes from caring too much about the outcome. 'What if I fail? What if they reject me?' The Gita says: just focus on doing your best. Let the result take care of itself. You control the effort, not the result." },
      { heading: "Stay Calm in Success and Failure", text: "BG 2.48 — 'Do your work with a calm mind. Do not cling to success or failure. This calmness is called yoga.' Life will give you wins and losses. The anxious mind swings between 'I need to win' and 'what if I lose.' Krishna says: stay steady. Do your best. Then let go. Peace is in the middle." },
      { heading: "Drop the 'What Ifs'", text: "BG 2.55 — 'When you drop all desires of the mind and feel complete within yourself, you have found real peace.' Anxiety is just 'what if' on repeat. What if I fail? What if they leave? What if things go wrong? All these are desires in disguise. Let them go. You are enough, right now, as you are." },
      { heading: "How to Stay Strong in Hard Times", text: "BG 2.56 — 'A wise person is not upset by pain, does not chase pleasure, and is free from fear and anger.' Anxiety makes you run from pain and cling to pleasure. But both are temporary. When hard times come, don't fight them. When good times come, don't cling to them. Stay steady. This too shall pass." },
      { heading: "Pleasure and Pain Are Temporary", text: "BG 2.14 — 'Pleasure and pain come and go like summer and winter. They are temporary. Learn to handle them with patience.' When you are anxious, you feel like this moment will last forever. It won't. The feeling will pass. The worry will fade. Just breathe. Wait it out. Nothing is permanent." },
      { heading: "Your Mind Creates Your Anxiety", text: "BG 2.62-63 — 'First you think about something. Then you want it. If you don't get it, you get angry. Anger clouds your mind. And you fall.' Anxiety follows the same path. You start thinking 'what if I mess up?' Then you spiral. Catch it at the first thought. Don't feed the worry. Stop the chain before it starts." },
      { heading: "Find the Calm Inside You", text: "BG 2.66 — 'A person who is agitated cannot have peace. Without peace, how can there be happiness?' You can't find peace by changing your circumstances. New job, new relationship, new city — the anxiety follows you. Peace is not outside. It is inside. Stop looking for it in the world. Find it in yourself." },
      { heading: "Be Like the Ocean, Not a Puddle", text: "BG 2.70 — 'The ocean stays calm even though rivers keep flowing into it. A person who remains calm amid desires is peaceful.' A puddle dries up when the sun comes out. The ocean stays full no matter what. Be the ocean. Let worries come and go without disturbing your depth. Stay deep, stay calm." },
      { heading: "Train Your Restless Mind", text: "BG 6.35 — 'The mind is restless, turbulent, and hard to control. But it can be trained by practice and detachment.' Your mind will jump from worry to worry. That is its nature. But you can train it. Every time you notice it wandering, gently bring it back. Like a puppy you are house-training. Practice. Patience. It gets easier." },
      { heading: "Gently Bring Your Mind Back", text: "BG 6.26 — 'Whenever the mind wanders, bring it back under the control of the self.' Your mind will run away a hundred times. That is okay. Each time you notice it and bring it back, you are building your mental muscle. Don't get frustrated. Just bring it back. Again and again. That is the practice." },
      { heading: "The Tortoise Trick for Anxiety", text: "BG 2.58 — 'When a person withdraws their senses like a tortoise pulls in its limbs, they become steady and wise.' When anxiety hits, pull back. Put your phone down. Close your eyes. Take a break. The tortoise knows when to retreat into its shell. You can do the same. Step back from the noise. Find your quiet." },
      { heading: "Lift Yourself Up", text: "BG 6.5 — 'Lift yourself up by your own effort. Do not put yourself down. You are your own best friend or your own worst enemy.' No one can fix your anxiety except you. Not your partner, not your therapist, not a pill. You have the power to pull yourself out. Talk to yourself like a friend, not a critic." },
      { heading: "Waves Come and Go — You Are the Ocean", text: "BG 6.6 — 'If you control your mind, it becomes your best friend. If you don't, it becomes your worst enemy.' Anxiety feels like waves crashing over you. But you are not the waves. You are the ocean. The waves rise and fall. The ocean stays. Watch your anxious thoughts like waves. They pass. You remain." },
      { heading: "Don't Let Fear Paralyze You", text: "BG 3.8 — 'Perform your duty. Action is better than inaction.' Anxiety tells you to freeze. To wait until you feel ready. But waiting makes it worse. Do something. Anything. Take a small step. Send that email. Make that call. Move your body. Action breaks the cycle of anxiety. Motion creates calm." },
      { heading: "Stop Trying to Control Everything", text: "BG 3.27 — 'All actions are carried out by nature. The ego says, \"I am doing this,\" but that is an illusion.' You think you need to control everything. But you can't. You are not in charge of the universe. Let go of the illusion of control. Do your part. Trust the rest. The weight will lift." },
      { heading: "Let Go and Trust", text: "BG 18.66 — 'Let go of everything and come to Me. Do not be afraid.' Surrender is not weakness. It is the ultimate relief. You have been carrying the weight of the world on your shoulders. Put it down. Trust that things will work out. Not because you controlled everything — but because you let go. Fear leaves when surrender enters." },
      { heading: "A Calm Mind Sees Clearly", text: "BG 2.65 — 'When the mind is calm, all suffering ends. The intellect becomes steady.' When you are anxious, you cannot think clearly. You make bad decisions. But when you calm down first, clarity comes. Before you solve any problem, calm your mind first. The answer will come. Trust the quiet." },
      { heading: "Real Strength Is Inner Peace", text: "BG 16.1-3 — 'Fearlessness, purity of heart, calmness, compassion — these are the qualities of a divine nature.' The world says strength is loud, aggressive, never backing down. Krishna says real strength is calm. It is being peaceful when everyone else is panicking. It is staying kind even when you are stressed. That is true power." },
      { heading: "You Have Been Through Worse", text: "BG 2.18 — 'The body is temporary. The soul is eternal. Fight on, O Arjuna.' Every anxious thought tells you that you can't handle it. But look back — you have survived 100% of your worst days. Every heartbreak, every failure, every scary moment. You are still here. You are stronger than your anxiety. Remember that." },
      { heading: "Peace Is Your True Nature", text: "BG 5.21 — 'One who finds happiness within, joy within, and light within — that person is truly free.' You have been searching for peace outside — in approval, money, relationships. But peace is your true nature. It is not something you get. It is something you remember. Sit quietly. Breathe. The peace has been inside you all along." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 4,
    title: "Discipline",
    scripture: "Chanakya Neeti",
    subtitle: "Real-life wisdom from Chanakya on self-control & habits.",
    source: "Explore Chanakya Neeti",
    bg: "#5C3D20",
    accent: "#D4A96A",
    emoji: "⚔️",
    image: BOOK_IMAGES[4] || null,
    sampleVerse: "The one who has conquered their own mind is the true winner. Conquering others is easy by comparison. — Chanakya Neeti 8.3",
    pages: [
      { heading: "Conquer Yourself First", text: "CN 8.3 — 'The one who has conquered their own mind is the true winner. Conquering others is easy by comparison.' The biggest battle is inside you. Your laziness, your excuses, your cravings — defeat those, and nothing outside can stop you. Self-control is the real strength." },
      { heading: "Start Today, Not Tomorrow", text: "CN 11.1 — 'Do not put off till tomorrow what can be done today.' Procrastination is a thief. It steals your time, your energy, and your dreams. If you keep saying 'I will start tomorrow,' tomorrow never comes. The best time to start was yesterday. The second best time is right now." },
      { heading: "Small Efforts Every Day Add Up", text: "CN 3.11 — 'There is no poverty for the industrious.' You don't need to do everything at once. Just do a little every day. Walk 10 minutes. Read 5 pages. Save 100 rupees. Small daily actions look boring, but they build like bricks. One day you will look back and see you have built a palace." },
      { heading: "Wake Up Before the Sun", text: "CN 4.5 — 'Wake up early in the Brahma Muhurta (the hour before sunrise) and focus on your goals.' The early morning is magic. The world is quiet. No calls, no messages, no noise. Use this time for yourself — stretch, plan, read, meditate. How you start your morning decides how your whole day goes." },
      { heading: "A Disciplined Body Leads to a Disciplined Mind", text: "CN 6.1 — 'Health is the greatest gift. Contentment is the greatest wealth.' If your body is weak, your mind will be weak. Eat well, sleep well, move every day. Discipline is not just about work — it is about taking care of the only body you have. A healthy body gives you a strong mind." },
      { heading: "Your Senses Will Try to Pull You Away", text: "CN 2.1 — 'The senses are wild horses. The wise person controls them with the reins of the mind.' Your phone will buzz, tasty food will call, your bed will feel warm. That is your senses testing you. Discipline means saying no to what feels good now for what is good for you later. Be the driver, not the horse." },
      { heading: "Keep Your Goal a Secret Until You Achieve It", text: "CN 1.12 — 'Do not reveal what you have planned. Keep it secret and act with determination.' When you tell everyone your goal, you get a rush of dopamine — and then you lose the motivation to actually do it. Keep your mouth shut. Let your results speak. The world pays attention to success, not plans." },
      { heading: "Practice Every Single Day", text: "CN 4.15 — 'Knowledge without practice is like poison.' You can watch a hundred workout videos — but if you never exercise, your body won't change. You can read a hundred business books — but if you never start, you will stay where you are. Discipline is not about knowing. It is about doing. Every single day." },
      { heading: "Do Not Waste Time on Trivial Things", text: "CN 10.1 — 'Time is like a river. You cannot touch the same water twice. Wasted time never returns.' Every hour you spend scrolling, overthinking, or procrastinating is an hour you will never get back. Treat time like money. Spend it wisely. Ask yourself: is what I am doing right now worth the hour of my life it costs?" },
      { heading: "The Fool Learns Nothing from Advice", text: "CN 1.4 — 'Teaching a fool is like planting a garden in the desert. No matter how much you water, nothing grows.' You can give a person all the best advice — but if they don't listen, it means nothing. Discipline starts with being teachable. If someone wiser gives you advice, listen. Apply it. Don't be the fool who knows everything but does nothing." },
      { heading: "Stay Away From Bad Company", text: "CN 1.6 — 'A bad friend is like a pot of poison. You may drink milk from it, but it will still kill you.' The people you surround yourself with will either lift you up or drag you down. If your friends waste time, you will too. If they are driven, you will be too. Discipline is easier when your circle matches your standards." },
      { heading: "One Steady Step Beats a Thousand Dashes", text: "CN 7.9 — 'Slow and steady wins the race. The turtle reaches the destination while the rabbit sleeps.' Don't try to change your life in one day. That is how people burn out. Do one thing. Do it well. Do it every day. Ten minutes of daily practice beats three hours done once a month. Consistency is the real superpower." },
      { heading: "Anger Destroys All Discipline", text: "CN 8.4 — 'Anger is the enemy of good judgment. A person overcome by anger loses everything they have built.' You can work hard for years, but one angry moment can ruin relationships, jobs, and reputations. Discipline is not just about routines — it is about controlling your temper. Breathe before you react. Stay calm. Stay in control." },
      { heading: "Patience Is the Foundation", text: "CN 9.3 — 'Patience is the root of all success. Without it, nothing great can be achieved.' Results take time. You won't get fit in a week. You won't get rich in a month. You won't master a skill in a year. Discipline requires patience. Trust the process. Keep showing up. The fruit will ripen when it is ready." },
      { heading: "Your Only Real Competition Is Yourself", text: "CN 11.4 — 'You should compare yourself only with yourself. See how much you have grown, not how far others are ahead.' Discipline is not about beating others. It's about being better than you were yesterday. Stop looking at what others are doing. Focus on your own journey. Run your own race." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 5,
    title: "Purpose",
    scripture: "Vivekananda",
    subtitle: "Find your dharma and live with clear intention.",
    source: "Explore Vivekananda",
    bg: "#6B4A18",
    accent: "#F0C060",
    emoji: "🌅",
    image: BOOK_IMAGES[5] || null,
    sampleVerse: "Arise, awake and stop not till the goal is reached. — Swami Vivekananda",
    pages: [
      { heading: "You Are Not Small", text: "Vivekananda said: the greatest sin is to think you are weak. You are not a drop in the ocean. You are the entire ocean in a drop. Your potential is infinite. Stop selling yourself short." },
      { heading: "Find Your Dharma", text: "Dharma means your true purpose. What makes you lose track of time? What would you do even if nobody paid you? That is your dharma. Your purpose is not outside you — it is already inside, waiting to be discovered." },
      { heading: "Serve Others", text: "The best way to find yourself is to lose yourself in service. Ask not what the world can give you. Ask what you can give. When your work helps others, it stops being a job and becomes a calling." },
      { heading: "One Idea, One Life", text: "Take up one idea. Make that one idea your life. Think of it, dream of it, live on that idea. Let your brain, muscles, nerves, every part of your body be full of that idea. This is the path to greatness." },
      { heading: "Have Faith in Yourself", text: "The world will doubt you. People will tell you that you can't. But the only opinion that matters is yours. Have faith in yourself. Faith moves mountains. If you believe you can, you are already halfway there." },
      { heading: "Action Over Talk", text: "It is easy to talk. It is hard to do. The difference between a dream and a goal is a deadline and action. Stop waiting for the perfect plan. Start. You will figure it out along the way." },
      { heading: "Learn Every Day", text: "Education is not just school. It is the manifestation of the perfection already in you. Read. Listen. Explore. Every day is a chance to become a better version of yourself. Never stop growing." },
      { heading: "Arise and Awake", text: "This is Vivekananda's famous call: arise, awake, and stop not till the goal is reached. Don't sleep through your life. Wake up to your potential. Start moving. And never, ever give up." },
      { heading: "Be Fearless", text: "Fear is the greatest obstacle to purpose. Fear of failure, fear of judgment, fear of the unknown. Vivekananda said: be fearless. The moment you conquer fear, you unlock your true potential. Courage is the foundation of all virtues." },
      { heading: "Give Without Expecting", text: "True joy comes from giving without expecting anything in return. Help someone because you can, not because they will help you back. When you give freely, the universe gives back to you in unexpected ways." },
      { heading: "Strength is Life", text: "Weakness is death. Strength is life. Vivekananda said this again and again. Build your physical strength. Build your mental strength. Build your spiritual strength. A strong person can help others. A weak person can only suffer." },
      { heading: "Question Everything", text: "Do not believe something just because it is written in a book or spoken by a guru. Question it. Test it. Experience it yourself. Truth is not found by believing. Truth is found by exploring. Be your own authority." },
      { heading: "Work as Worship", text: "Whatever you do, do it with full heart. Wash dishes like it is a prayer. Type emails like you are writing poetry. When you bring devotion to your work, work becomes worship. There is no task too small for love." },
      { heading: "Expand Your Vision", text: "You are not just this small body and this small mind. You are part of the infinite. Think bigger. Dream bigger. The same power that moves the stars moves through you. Do not limit yourself with small thinking." },
      { heading: "Be a Light Unto Yourself", text: "Ultimately, you are your own guide. Teachers can show you the door, but you must walk through it. Trust your inner wisdom. You have everything you need inside you. Be your own light." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 6,
    title: "Focus",
    scripture: "Yoga Sutras",
    subtitle: "Patanjali's Yoga Sutras for focus in a distracted world.",
    source: "Explore Yoga Sutras",
    bg: "#4A3A6B",
    accent: "#B0A0D8",
    emoji: "🧘",
    image: BOOK_IMAGES[6] || null,
    sampleVerse: "Yoga is the settling of the mind into silence. — Patanjali Yoga Sutra 1.2",
    pages: [
      { heading: "What Is Focus Really?", text: "YS 1.2 — 'Yoga is the settling of the mind's movements into silence.' Your mind jumps between thoughts like a monkey swinging from branch to branch. Focus is not about forcing stillness. It is about gently settling down. Like mud settling in still water. Let the thoughts settle on their own." },
      { heading: "Two Things You Need: Practice and Letting Go", text: "YS 1.12 — 'Practice and detachment are the two methods to calm the mind.' You cannot just wish to focus. You have to practice — every day, a little bit. And you have to let go — of the frustration, the impatience, the 'why can't I focus?' Keep practicing. Keep letting go. That is the whole game." },
      { heading: "Practice Means Showing Up Every Day", text: "YS 1.13-14 — 'Practice is the effort to stay steady. It becomes firm when done for a long time without a break.' 5 minutes every day beats 2 hours once a week. Patanjali says: consistency is everything. Don't worry about progress. Just keep showing up. The mind learns slowly. Be patient." },
      { heading: "Let Go of the Little Cravings", text: "YS 1.15 — 'Detachment is freedom from craving for pleasures, seen or unseen.' Your phone buzzes. You crave to check. A thought pops up. You crave to follow it. Focus is broken not by distractions — but by your craving for them. Let the craving go. It will pass. Stay with your task." },
      { heading: "The Five Movements of the Mind", text: "YS 1.5-6 — 'The mind has five movements: right knowledge, wrong knowledge, imagination, sleep, and memory. Some create peace, some create disturbance.' Your mind is not a single thing. It has different gears. Sometimes you are thinking clearly. Sometimes you are imagining. Sometimes you are half asleep. Different movements need different methods. Know what gear your mind is in, then choose the right approach." },
      { heading: "Right Knowledge vs Wrong Knowledge", text: "YS 1.7-8 — 'Right knowledge comes from direct perception, logical inference, and trustworthy testimony. Wrong knowledge is based on false understanding.' Not all thoughts are true. Some thoughts are just wrong assumptions. You think 'I will fail' — that is wrong knowledge. You think 'they don't like me' — maybe that is just your mind playing tricks. Question your thoughts. Don't believe everything you think." },
      { heading: "Imagination and Sleep Are Mental States Too", text: "YS 1.9-10 — 'Imagination is based on words without real substance. Sleep is the mind turning inward, aware of nothing.' Even when you are daydreaming or sleeping, your mind is active. Imagination is useful — it lets you create. But when imagination turns into worry about things that never happened, it steals your focus. Know when to create and when to come back to reality." },
      { heading: "Memory: Friend or Foe?", text: "YS 1.11 — 'Memory is keeping hold of past experiences.' Memory is useful. You remember how to drive. You remember your loved ones. But memory can also be a trap. You keep replaying old hurts. You keep remembering past failures. Patanjali says: use memory when you need it. Let it go when you don't. Don't live in the past." },
      { heading: "Supreme Detachment: Freedom From Everything", text: "YS 1.16 — 'Supreme detachment is freedom from craving even the highest pleasures. When you know the Self, you stop craving anything.' Letting go of your phone for 5 minutes is one kind of detachment. But true freedom is when you don't need anything outside yourself to feel complete. That is the highest focus — nothing disturbs you because nothing is missing." },
      { heading: "Stages of Deep Focus: From Thinking to Silence", text: "YS 1.17-18 — 'Deep focus has stages: analyzing, feeling bliss, sensing the self, and finally pure silence beyond all thought.' In the beginning, your mind is busy. Then it settles into bliss. Then you feel your true self. And finally, even that feeling dissolves into pure silence. Each stage is deeper than the last. Don't rush. Let focus deepen naturally." },
      { heading: "Surrender to Something Greater", text: "YS 1.23-24 — 'By surrendering to God, you can also reach the goal. God is a special being untouched by afflictions, actions, or karma.' Some people focus through willpower. Others focus through love and surrender. If you feel tired of trying so hard, just surrender. Say 'I give this to the universe.' Sometimes letting go of control is the best way to focus." },
      { heading: "The Power of Chanting Aum", text: "YS 1.27-28 — 'The symbol of God is the sound Aum. Chant it and meditate on its meaning.' Ancient sages discovered that certain sounds calm the mind. Aum is the most powerful. Just chanting Aum for a few minutes settles your nerves and brings your mind to one point. Try it next time you cannot focus. Sit quietly and chant Aum. Feel the vibration." },
      { heading: "Signs Your Focus Has Broken", text: "YS 1.30-31 — 'The obstacles are disease, laziness, doubt, carelessness, craving, losing focus, and restlessness. When these appear, you feel pain, depression, and shaky breathing.' Patanjali gives you a checklist. If you are feeling depressed, restless, or your breathing is uneven — these are signs your focus is broken. The solution is not to fight harder. Address the root cause. Rest first." },
      { heading: "One Principle to Fix All Distractions", text: "YS 1.32 — 'To overcome all obstacles, practice one single principle.' When everything is going wrong, don't try ten different techniques. Pick one. Just one. Your breath. One mantra. One point. The simple act of focusing on one thing cuts through all chaos. Less is more when it comes to focus." },
      { heading: "Be Kind to Others, Calm Your Mind", text: "YS 1.33 — 'Cultivate friendliness toward the happy, compassion for the unhappy, joy for the virtuous, and equanimity toward the wicked. This brings peace to the mind.' Your focus breaks when you are angry at someone, jealous of someone, or annoyed by someone. Clear your relationships, clear your mind. Peace with others = peace within." },
      { heading: "Your Breath Is Your Anchor", text: "YS 1.34 — 'Focusing on the breath calms the mind.' The simplest focus trick is older than any app. Just feel your breath. In, out. When your mind wanders, bring it back to the breath. Not forcefully. Gently. Like bringing a child back home. The breath is always there, always present." },
      { heading: "Focus Through the Senses", text: "YS 1.35 — 'Focus on a sense experience — smell, taste, sight, touch, or sound — and the mind becomes steady.' If breath doesn't work for you, try something else. Focus on the flame of a candle. Listen to a sound. Feel the texture of a stone. Your senses are gateways to focus. Use whatever works." },
      { heading: "Your Inner Light Never Distracts", text: "YS 1.36 — 'Focus on the inner light, which is beyond sorrow.' When external distractions are too much, close your eyes and turn inward. There is a light inside you — calm, steady, never distracted. Focus on that. The world can wait. Your inner stillness is always available." },
      { heading: "Focus on What Uplifts You", text: "YS 1.37-39 — 'Focus on a mind free of craving. Or reflect on dreamless sleep. Or focus on whatever appeals to you.' There is no one right way to focus. If a method feels forced, try another. Look at a mountain. Remember a peaceful dream. Think of someone you love. Patanjali says: use whatever naturally brings you peace. The method doesn't matter. The result does." },
      { heading: "Mastery From Small to Infinite", text: "YS 1.40-41 — 'Mastery of focus extends from the smallest atom to the largest infinity. The mind becomes like a clear jewel, taking the shape of whatever it reflects.' When your focus is pure, you can understand anything. The smallest details and the biggest ideas — all become clear. Your mind stops adding its own noise. It becomes a perfect mirror." },
      { heading: "The Five Afflictions That Break Focus", text: "YS 2.3-4 — 'The five afflictions are ignorance, ego, attachment, aversion, and fear of death. Ignorance is the root of them all.' You cannot focus when you are afraid. Or when your ego is hurt. Or when you are clinging to something. These afflictions are like background noise. You cannot hear clearly when they are playing. Remove the noise, and focus comes naturally." },
      { heading: "Ignorance: Mistaking the Temporary for Permanent", text: "YS 2.5 — 'Ignorance is mistaking the impermanent for permanent, the impure for pure, pain for pleasure, and the non-self for the self.' You chase things that will not last. You avoid things that would help you grow. That is ignorance. When you see clearly what matters and what doesn't, focus becomes effortless." },
      { heading: "Ego, Attachment, Aversion, Fear", text: "YS 2.6-9 — 'Ego is identifying the self with the mind. Attachment is clinging to pleasure. Aversion is avoiding pain. Fear of death is instinctive, even in the wise.' These four afflictions are like four thieves stealing your attention. Ego makes you defensive. Attachment makes you cling. Aversion makes you run. Fear makes you freeze. Recognize them, and they lose their power." },
      { heading: "Remove Afflictions Through Meditation", text: "YS 2.10-11 — 'Subtle afflictions are destroyed by reversing their cause. Active afflictions are destroyed through meditation.' Some problems are deep, like old habits. Some are on the surface, like today's worry. For deep problems, sit and watch them silently — they will dissolve. For surface problems, just meditate for a few minutes. Both methods work." },
      { heading: "The Eight Limbs of Yoga for Focus", text: "YS 2.29 — 'The eight limbs are: yama (ethics), niyama (habits), asana (posture), pranayama (breath), pratyahara (sense withdrawal), dharana (concentration), dhyana (meditation), and samadhi (absorption).' Focus is not just about the last three limbs. You need all eight. Ethics clear your mind. Habits build discipline. Posture supports stillness. Breath calms your nerves. Withdrawing senses turns you inward. Everything works together." },
      { heading: "Counter Negative Thoughts With Positive", text: "YS 2.33-34 — 'When disturbed by negative thoughts, cultivate the opposite. Negative thoughts — violence, lies, greed — cause infinite pain. Counter them with their opposites.' Your mind will have dark thoughts. That is normal. Don't fight them directly. Instead, bring in the opposite. If you feel angry, think of kindness. If you feel greedy, think of giving. Light dispels darkness naturally." },
      { heading: "One Point, One Mind", text: "YS 3.1 — 'Concentration (dharana) is fixing the mind on one single point.' The world tells you to multitask. Patanjali says: pick one thing. Give it your whole mind. Not half your mind on work and half on your phone. One thing. Fully. That is concentration." },
      { heading: "Sustained Focus Is Meditation", text: "YS 3.2 — 'Meditation (dhyana) is the steady flow of attention toward one point.' Concentration is when you keep bringing the mind back. Meditation is when it finally stays. Like a river flowing continuously. Not stopping, not wandering. Just flowing toward one thing. Keep practicing. You will get there." },
      { heading: "Total Absorption Is Samadhi", text: "YS 3.3 — 'Samadhi is when the object alone shines, as if the mind has dissolved into it.' This is the deepest focus. You forget yourself. You forget time. Only the task exists. The artist becomes the painting. The musician becomes the music. You have felt this in flow states. Samadhi is the ultimate flow." },
      { heading: "Samyama: The Combined Practice", text: "YS 3.4-6 — 'Concentration, meditation, and absorption together are called samyama. Master it step by step.' Don't jump to the deepest level. First learn to concentrate. Then sustain it into meditation. Then let it deepen into absorption. Each stage prepares you for the next. Be patient. The journey is the goal." },
      { heading: "Effort Plus Relaxation Equals Focus", text: "YS 2.47 — 'Posture becomes perfect when effort is relaxed and the mind is absorbed in the infinite.' Focus is not about forcing. It is about balancing effort and ease. Try too hard and you get tense. Too relaxed and you drift. Find the middle. Effort + surrender. Like holding a bird — not too tight, not too loose." },
      { heading: "Master Your Breath, Master Your Mind", text: "YS 2.49-53 — 'Pranayama is regulating the breath. It removes the veil over the inner light. The mind becomes ready for concentration.' When you control your breath, you control your mind. Fast breathing = anxiety. Shallow breathing = fatigue. Slow, deep breathing = focus. Before any important task, take 10 deep breaths. Your mind will follow your breath." },
      { heading: "Withdraw the Senses to Focus Inward", text: "YS 2.54-55 — 'Pratyahara is withdrawing the senses from their objects. Then the senses obey the mind, not the outside world.' Your eyes want to look. Your ears want to listen. Your fingers want to scroll. Pratyahara is the power to say 'not now.' When you can turn off the outside world, your inner world becomes crystal clear." },
      { heading: "Don't Let Failure Break Your Practice", text: "YS 1.30 — 'Disease, laziness, doubt, carelessness, craving, and losing focus — these are the obstacles.' Patanjali lists nine obstacles. Notice: he doesn't say avoid them. He says they will come. The key is not to never fail. The key is to start again when you do. One slip doesn't ruin the practice." },
      { heading: "Progress Comes Step by Step", text: "YS 2.1 — 'Yoga of action has three parts: discipline, self-study, and surrender to something greater.' You cannot become a master of focus overnight. First comes discipline — just show up. Then self-study — learn how your mind works. Then surrender — let go of the outcome. Step by step. That is the path." },
      { heading: "When Disturbances Stop Bothering You", text: "YS 2.48 — 'When posture is mastered, the pairs of opposites cease to bother you.' Heat and cold, noise and silence, praise and blame — they stop disturbing you. When your focus is deep, the world fades. Not because the world changed. Because you changed. You are no longer at the mercy of your surroundings." },
      { heading: "Freedom Through Focus", text: "YS 4.30-34 — 'From the highest meditation comes freedom from afflictions. The gunas (qualities of nature) cease their purpose. The Self settles into its own nature.' The ultimate goal of all this focus work is not productivity. It is freedom. Freedom from being pushed around by your thoughts. Freedom from distraction. Freedom to rest in your own true nature. That is the real prize." },
      { heading: "The Stillness You Seek Is Already Inside You", text: "YS 4.34 — 'The goal of yoga is the freedom of the Self, where the mind settles into its original stillness.' You are not trying to create focus. You are uncovering it. It is already there, underneath the noise. Like the sun behind the clouds. The clouds will pass. The sun was always there. So is your focus." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 7,
    title: "Success",
    scripture: "Arthashastra",
     subtitle: "Kautilya's Arthashastra — strategic wisdom for wealth and power.",
    source: "Explore Arthashastra",
    bg: "#3A5040",
    accent: "#90C8A0",
    emoji: "🏆",
    image: BOOK_IMAGES[7] || null,
    sampleVerse: "In the happiness of his subjects lies the happiness of the king. — Kautilya Arthashastra 1.19",
    pages: [
      { heading: "The Real Meaning of Success", text: "Arthashastra 1.19 — 'In the happiness of his subjects lies the happiness of the king. In their welfare, his welfare.' True success is not about how much you have. It is about how many lives you improve. Your success is meaningless if it helps no one but yourself. Serve others, and success will follow." },
      { heading: "The Three Powers of Success", text: "Arthashastra 6.1 — 'The king's power has three parts: intellectual power, sovereign power, and physical power.' You need all three. Intellectual power — knowledge. Sovereign power — money and resources. Physical power — health and energy. Work on all three. One is not enough." },
      { heading: "Know Yourself First", text: "Arthashastra 1.8 — 'A king should know his own strengths and weaknesses before judging others.' Success starts with self-awareness. What are you good at? What do you struggle with? Don't lie to yourself. Face the truth. Know where you stand before planning where to go." },
      { heading: "Study Philosophy and Economics", text: "Arthashastra 1.2-3 — 'Philosophy illuminates what is right and wrong. The three Vedas teach duty. Economics provides wealth.' Kautilya says you need all three kinds of knowledge. Philosophy gives you direction. Ethics guide your actions. Economics gives you resources. Don't be only spiritual or only material. Be both." },
      { heading: "Train Yourself Before You Lead Others", text: "Arthashastra 1.10 — 'A prince should be trained from childhood in the arts, sciences, and self-discipline.' Kautilya believed leaders are made, not born. Learn self-control before you try to control anything else. Learn discipline before you ask others to be disciplined. Training is not optional. It is the foundation." },
      { heading: "The First Rule: Control Your Senses", text: "Arthashastra 1.6 — 'A king who has conquered his senses can conquer the world. One who has not will be destroyed by his own desires.' Kautilya puts self-control above everything. If you cannot say no to your own cravings, you will make bad decisions. Master your desires for food, pleasure, anger, and pride. Everything else follows." },
      { heading: "Plan With Care, Act With Confidence", text: "Arthashastra 1.15 — 'Every action should be examined three times: its beginning, its middle, and its end.' Think before you leap. What will happen when you start? What challenges will come in the middle? How will it end? If you can answer these three, you are ready." },
      { heading: "Wisdom From Elders and Experience", text: "Arthashastra 1.5 — 'A king who learns from elders grows wise. A king who relies only on his own knowledge will make mistakes.' You don't know everything. No one does. Seek out people who have been where you want to go. Listen to their advice. Learn from their mistakes. Success is faster when you stand on the shoulders of others." },
      { heading: "Time Is Your Most Precious Resource", text: "Arthashastra 7.11 — 'A king who procrastinates loses his kingdom.' Kautilya was ruthless about time. Every delay costs you something — money, energy, or opportunity. Don't waste time on things that don't matter. Don't delay what needs to be done. Time waits for no one." },
      { heading: "Surround Yourself With Truth-Tellers", text: "Arthashastra 1.12 — 'The king should appoint ministers who are wise, loyal, and honest — people who will tell him the truth even when it hurts.' Flatterers will ruin you. Yes-men will destroy your growth. Keep people around who tell you hard truths with love." },
      { heading: "Learn From Your Enemies Too", text: "Arthashastra 9.1 — 'A wise king learns from friend and foe alike.' Watch your competitors. Study your critics. Your enemy knows your weaknesses better than your friend does. There is always a lesson hidden in criticism." },
      { heading: "Keep Your Plans Secret", text: "Arthashastra 1.13 — 'Counsel with wise men, but let the counsel remain secret.' Not everyone needs to know your plans. Share only with those who need to know. Silence is a powerful tool. Let your results do the talking." },
      { heading: "Gather Intelligence Before Decisions", text: "Arthashastra 1.14 — 'Spies should observe everyone — ministers, citizens, and enemies. Knowledge of the truth is the foundation of success.' Kautilya was famous for his spy network. In modern terms: do your research. Gather data. Understand the situation fully before making a decision. A decision based on rumors is a gamble. A decision based on facts is strategy." },
      { heading: "Flexibility Beats Rigidity", text: "Arthashastra 7.17 — 'The king who is always rigid will be broken. The king who adapts will survive.' Life is not a straight line. Sometimes you bend, sometimes you change direction completely. Adapt to the situation. Do the right thing at the right time." },
      { heading: "The Seven Pillars of Your Kingdom", text: "Arthashastra 6.2 — 'The state has seven constituents: the king, ministers, territory, fort, treasury, army, and allies.' Think of your life the same way. You are the king (leader). Your mentors are ministers. Your home is territory. Your savings are the fort. Your wealth is the treasury. Your skills are the army. Your friends are allies. Keep all seven strong." },
      { heading: "Take Care of Your Resources", text: "Arthashastra 2.1 — 'The treasury and the army are the roots of the state.' Today, your treasury is your savings. Your army is your skills. Protect both. Save money. Build skills. If you lose one, you still have the other. That is real security." },
      { heading: "Wealth Comes From Activity, Ruin From Laziness", text: "Arthashastra 2.2 — 'The superintendent should be active and careful. The root of wealth is activity. The root of destruction is laziness.' Kautilya says: keep moving. Keep working. Keep improving. Laziness is the beginning of the end. Even small, consistent effort beats occasional bursts of hard work. Be steady. Be active." },
      { heading: "Trade and Value Creation", text: "Arthashastra 2.6 — 'Trade should be promoted. Goods should flow freely. The king should remove obstacles to trade.' You succeed by creating value for others. Find what people need and provide it. Remove obstacles for your customers. Make things easier for others. The more value you create, the more success comes to you." },
      { heading: "A Leader Must Be Approachable", text: "Arthashastra 1.19 — 'The king who is inaccessible will never know the truth about his kingdom.' If you hide in your office, behind your title, or in your comfort zone, you lose touch with reality. Stay humble. Listen. The best leaders are the most approachable." },
      { heading: "Justice and Fair Punishment", text: "Arthashastra 4.1 — 'Punishment must be fair and just. Too harsh creates fear. Too soft creates chaos. Justice maintains order.' In your life, this means: hold yourself and others accountable. Be firm but fair. Don't let bad behavior slide, but don't be cruel either. Balance is the key to good leadership." },
      { heading: "Marriage, Family, and Support Systems", text: "Arthashastra 3.1 — 'Marriage is the foundation of family. Family is the foundation of society.' Kautilya understood that personal life and professional success are connected. A stable home supports ambitious work. Take care of your family. Build a strong personal foundation. Success at work means nothing if your home is in chaos." },
      { heading: "Crisis Is a Hidden Opportunity", text: "Arthashastra 9.7 — 'When an enemy rises, the wise king sees an opportunity to strengthen his own position.' Problems are not just problems. They are chances to grow. When things go wrong, ask: what can I learn? How can I use this? Every crisis hides a gift." },
      { heading: "The Six Measures of Diplomacy", text: "Arthashastra 7.1 — 'The six measures are: peace, war, neutrality, preparation, alliance, and double policy.' You don't use the same strategy in every situation. Sometimes you compromise. Sometimes you fight. Sometimes you wait. Sometimes you build alliances. Know which strategy fits which situation. One size does not fit all." },
      { heading: "Knowledge Is the Ultimate Power", text: "Arthashastra 1.5 — 'A king without knowledge will be deceived even by his own ministers.' Kautilya wrote the Arthashastra after years of study. He believed knowledge protects you. Read. Learn. Stay curious. Those who stop learning will be left behind." },
      { heading: "Lead by Example, Not by Words", text: "Arthashastra 1.7 — 'The king's conduct becomes the standard for the people.' People watch what you do, not what you say. If you want discipline, be disciplined. If you want kindness, be kind. Your actions set the tone for everyone around you." },
      { heading: "Choose Peace When Possible", text: "Arthashastra 7.15 — 'When the benefits of peace outweigh the benefits of war, choose peace.' Not every battle needs to be fought. Not every argument needs to be won. Sometimes the smartest move is to make peace. Know when to fight and when to forgive. Wisdom is knowing the difference." },
      { heading: "The Self-Made Leader", text: "Arthashastra 1.9 — 'A king should personally inspect his kingdom. He should not delegate everything.' Don't lose touch with the details. Yes, delegate. But also stay involved. Understand your business. Know your people. A leader who is disconnected from reality makes bad decisions. Stay hands-on where it matters." },
      { heading: "Your Army Is Your Skills", text: "Arthashastra 9.1 — 'The army should be trained, motivated, and well-equipped. A weak army invites attack.' In modern terms: invest in your skills. Keep learning. Keep practicing. Stay sharp. If your skills become outdated, you become vulnerable. Your skills are your army. Train them every day." },
      { heading: "Purpose Over Profit", text: "Arthashastra 1.4 — 'The king's duty is to create a society where everyone can thrive.' Success is not about having the most toys. It is about building something that outlasts you. A business that helps people. A family that loves each other. That is the Arthashastra way." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 8,
    title: "Health",
    scripture: "Ayurveda",
     subtitle: "Ancient Ayurvedic wisdom for body, mind and vitality.",
    source: "Explore Ayurveda",
    bg: "#3D6040",
    accent: "#A8D8A0",
    emoji: "🌿",
    image: BOOK_IMAGES[8] || null,
    sampleVerse: "When diet is wrong, medicine is of no use. When diet is correct, medicine is of no need. — Charaka Samhita",
    pages: [
      { heading: "You Are Born Unique", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.1 — 'Each person is born with a unique constitution — their Prakriti. Health means living in harmony with it.' Ayurveda says there are three doshas: Vata (air), Pitta (fire), Kapha (earth). What works for your friend may not work for you. Listen to YOUR body." },
      { heading: "Know Your Dosha: Vata", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.8 — 'Vata is dry, light, cold, subtle, and mobile. It governs movement, breath, and creativity.' If Vata is your main dosha, you are creative, energetic, and quick-thinking. But when imbalanced, you get anxious, forgetful, and restless. Keep warm. Eat warm, oily foods. Maintain a routine. Routine is medicine for Vata." },
      { heading: "Know Your Dosha: Pitta", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.9 — 'Pitta is hot, sharp, liquid, and slightly oily. It governs digestion, metabolism, and intelligence.' If Pitta is your main dosha, you are focused, ambitious, and sharp. But when imbalanced, you get angry, irritable, and inflamed. Stay cool. Eat cooling foods. Avoid spicy and fried food. Don't skip meals — Pitta gets angry when hungry." },
      { heading: "Know Your Dosha: Kapha", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.10 — 'Kapha is heavy, slow, cool, oily, and stable. It governs structure, strength, and immunity.' If Kapha is your main dosha, you are calm, strong, and loyal. But when imbalanced, you feel heavy, sluggish, and attached. Stay active. Eat light, warm foods. Avoid dairy and sweets. Wake up early. Movement is medicine for Kapha." },
      { heading: "Food Is Your First Medicine", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.27 — 'Food is the best medicine. No medicine can replace proper food.' Eat real food. Not packaged or processed. Vegetables, fruits, grains, lentils. Eat according to the season. Warm food in winter. Light food in summer. Your kitchen is your pharmacy." },
      { heading: "The Six Tastes of Life", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.26 — 'There are six tastes: sweet, sour, salty, pungent, bitter, and astringent. Each balances different doshas.' Your meal should include all six tastes. Sweet (grains, fruits) gives energy. Sour (lemon, yogurt) aids digestion. Salty (salt) maintains minerals. Pungent (ginger, chili) stimulates. Bitter (greens, turmeric) cleanses. Astringent (beans, pomegranate) tones. Variety is health." },
      { heading: "Your Daily Routine Shapes Your Health", text: "Ashtanga Hridaya 2.1 — 'Wake up early, drink warm water, stretch, and align with the sun's rhythm.' Ayurveda calls this Dinacharya. Wake before sunrise. Drink warm water. Stretch. Eat your biggest meal at lunch. Sleep by 10 PM. Aligning with nature's rhythm keeps you healthy." },
      { heading: "Morning Rituals for the Day", text: "Ashtanga Hridaya 2.2 — 'Upon waking, scrape your tongue, brush your teeth, and drink warm water. Then eliminate and bathe.' Small morning habits set the tone. Scrape your tongue to remove toxins. Drink warm water to wake your digestion. Oil pulling (swishing oil in your mouth) strengthens teeth and gums. These 5 minutes in the morning transform your health." },
      { heading: "Digestion Is the Root of Everything", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.12 — 'When Agni (digestive fire) is strong, health is strong. When it is weak, disease enters.' Health starts in the gut. Don't overeat. Don't eat when stressed. Don't drink cold water with meals. Eat mindfully. Chew properly. Your digestion decides your health." },
      { heading: "The Three Pillars of Life", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.21 — 'The three pillars of life are: Ahara (food), Nidra (sleep), and Brahmacharya (self-control).' If these three are strong, you are healthy. If even one is weak, your health suffers. Check yourself daily: did I eat well? Did I sleep well? Did I practice moderation? Three simple questions for lifelong health." },
      { heading: "Sleep Repairs Your Whole Being", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.21 — 'Sleep (Nidra) is one of the three pillars of life. Proper sleep brings happiness, strength, and longevity.' Sleep is when your body repairs itself. Without enough sleep, you cannot be healthy. Aim for 7-8 hours. Go to bed before 10 PM. No phones in bed. Sleep quality = life quality." },
      { heading: "Movement Is Life", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.30 — 'Those who exercise regularly stay healthy and live long.' You don't need a gym. Walk. Stretch. Do yoga. Dance. Move every day. Your body was designed for movement. Sitting all day is slowly killing you. Move for at least 30 minutes daily." },
      { heading: "Stress Is the Root of Disease", text: "Sushruta Samhita 1.25 — 'Mental stress disturbs the doshas and leads to disease.' When you are stressed, your digestion stops, your immunity drops, and your sleep suffers. Meditate. Breathe. Spend time in nature. Do nothing sometimes. A calm mind is the foundation of a healthy body." },
      { heading: "The Three Vital Essences: Ojas, Tejas, Prana", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.30 — 'Ojas is the essence of vitality. Tejas is the fire of transformation. Prana is the life force.' Ojas gives you immunity and strength. Tejas gives you intelligence and digestion. Prana gives you breath and energy. Good food builds Ojas. Good thoughts build Tejas. Good breathing builds Prana. Nourish all three." },
      { heading: "Prevention Is Better Than Cure", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.2 — 'Ayurveda's goal is to preserve the health of the healthy and treat the disease of the sick.' Don't wait until you are sick to take care of yourself. Eat well, sleep well, move well, think well. Health is not a goal. It is a way of living." },
      { heading: "Listen to Your Body's Signals", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.18 — 'The body gives warning signs before disease manifests. Pay attention to them.' A headache says: slow down. Indigestion says: you ate the wrong thing. Fatigue says: rest. Learn to read your body's signals. It is smarter than any doctor when you pay attention." },
      { heading: "Clean Your Body From Inside", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.16 — 'The body accumulates toxins (ama) from improper digestion. Fasting and cleansing remove them.' Sometimes your body needs a break. Skip a meal. Drink warm water with lemon. Eat only light foods for a day. This gives your digestion a rest and lets your body clean itself. Ayurveda calls this Langhana — lightening therapy." },
      { heading: "Eat With the Seasons", text: "Ashtanga Hridaya 3.1 — 'Eat according to the season for perfect health.' Nature provides different foods in different seasons. In summer, eat cooling foods like cucumber and melon. In winter, eat warming soups and root vegetables. In spring, eat light and cleansing foods. In autumn, eat sweet and oily foods. Eat in harmony with nature." },
      { heading: "Seasonal Cleansing for Long Life", text: "Ashtanga Hridaya 3.2 — 'At the change of seasons, the body needs cleansing. This prevents disease.' Every three months, when the season changes, do a gentle cleanse. Eat light foods. Drink warm water with ginger. Avoid heavy, oily, or cold foods. This keeps your body adaptable and prevents seasonal illnesses like colds and allergies." },
      { heading: "Drink Water Like a Ritual", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.27 — 'Sip warm water throughout the day. Cold water weakens Agni.' Sip warm water. Avoid ice-cold water with meals — it weakens digestion. Drink when you are thirsty, not out of habit. Best time to drink water? First thing in the morning on an empty stomach." },
      { heading: "Oil Your Body, Nourish Your Skin", text: "Ashtanga Hridaya 2.10 — 'Abhyanga (oil massage) nourishes the skin, calms the nerves, and improves sleep.' Even 5 minutes of warm oil massage before a bath can transform your health. Sesame oil in winter, coconut oil in summer. Your skin absorbs what you put on it." },
      { heading: "Breathe to Balance Your Mind", text: "Sushruta Samhita 4.23 — 'Pranayama balances the body and mind.' Alternate nostril breathing is a simple technique. Close right nostril, inhale through left. Close left, exhale through right. Then reverse. This harmonizes your brain and calms your nervous system. Try it for 5 minutes." },
      { heading: "Good Conduct Is Good Health", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.17 — 'Sadvritta (good conduct) is as important as good food. Speak kindly, act honestly, and respect others.' Your health is not just about what you eat. It is about how you live. Be truthful. Be compassionate. Forgive. These are not just moral rules. They are health practices. Anger and dishonesty create toxins in the body." },
      { heading: "The Power of Fasting", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.15 — 'Fasting gives the digestive system a rest and removes toxins. It brings lightness to the body and clarity to the mind.' You don't have to fast for days. Just skip one meal. Or eat only fruits for a day. Your body uses this time to clean itself. Modern science confirms: intermittent fasting reduces inflammation and increases longevity." },
      { heading: "Eat Big at Lunch, Light at Dinner", text: "Ashtanga Hridaya 2.8 — 'Eat your largest meal at midday when Agni is strongest.' Your digestion is strongest when the sun is at its peak. Eat a big lunch and a light dinner. This aligns with your natural rhythm and prevents weight gain, indigestion, and poor sleep." },
      { heading: "Rejuvenation for Long Life", text: "Charaka Samhita 2.1 — 'Rasayana (rejuvenation) slows aging, improves immunity, and increases vitality.' Simple rejuvenation practices: eat fresh, seasonal foods. Meditate daily. Practice gratitude. Get enough sleep. Nourish your relationships. The path to long life is not complicated. It is just consistent small daily habits." },
      { heading: "Happiness Heals", text: "Charaka Samhita 1.15 — 'A happy mind creates a healthy body. Sattva (mental purity) is the foundation of health.' Laughter, joy, and contentment boost your immunity. Stress, anger, and sadness weaken it. Cultivate happiness. It is not just good for your mind — it is your best medicine." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 9,
    title: "Inner Peace",
    scripture: "Upanishads",
     subtitle: "Upanishadic wisdom to discover the stillness within.",
    source: "Explore Upanishads",
    bg: "#5C4A2A",
    accent: "#E0C080",
    emoji: "☀️",
    image: BOOK_IMAGES[9] || null,
    sampleVerse: "Tat Tvam Asi — That you are. — Chandogya Upanishad 6.8.7",
    pages: [
      { heading: "You Are Already Complete", text: "Chandogya Upanishad 6.8.7 — 'Tat Tvam Asi — That you are.' The same consciousness that runs the universe runs you. You are not broken. You don't need to be fixed. You just need to remember who you already are. The peace you seek is your own true nature." },
      { heading: "You Are the Sky, Not the Clouds", text: "Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 4.4.22 — 'The Self is beyond thought. It is the witness of the mind.' You are not your thoughts. You are not your emotions. You are the awareness behind them. Imagine you are the sky. Thoughts are clouds. They come and go. The sky remains clear and unchanged." },
      { heading: "Drop All Labels", text: "Chandogya Upanishad 6.1.4 — 'By knowing one thing, everything becomes known. By knowing the Self, all is known.' I am this. I am that. I am successful. I am a failure. These labels are cages. Drop them. Stop identifying with your stories. What is left when the labels fall away? That is your true self." },
      { heading: "Stillness Speaks the Loudest", text: "Mundaka Upanishad 3.2.3 — 'The Self cannot be grasped by words or by the mind. It is realized in the silence of the heart.' Stop chasing experiences. Stop filling every moment with noise. Sit quietly for 10 minutes every day. In the stillness, you find answers that noise cannot give." },
      { heading: "The Four Great Sayings: Aham Brahmasmi", text: "Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 1.4.10 — 'Aham Brahmasmi — I am Brahman. I am the vast, infinite reality.' Not 'I will become Brahman.' Not 'I am like Brahman.' I AM Brahman. Right now. In this very moment. Not after years of meditation. Not after you become perfect. This is the highest teaching: you are already the infinite." },
      { heading: "The Four Great Sayings: Prajnanam Brahma", text: "Aitareya Upanishad 3.1.3 — 'Prajnanam Brahma — Consciousness is Brahman.' Pure awareness — without thought, without emotion, without any content — that is the ultimate reality. You don't need to achieve consciousness. You ARE consciousness. Everything else is just something passing through." },
      { heading: "The Four Great Sayings: Ayam Atma Brahma", text: "Mandukya Upanishad 2 — 'Ayam Atma Brahma — This Self is Brahman.' The self inside you and the reality outside you are the same thing. There is no separation. The table is you. The sky is you. The person you love and the person you struggle with — they are all you. When you see this, how can you not be at peace?" },
      { heading: "The World Is a Passing Dream", text: "Katha Upanishad 2.1.1 — 'This world is like a fig tree — it seems real, but its roots are in the unseen.' The world feels real when you are in it, but it is temporary. Don't cling too tightly to any experience. Enjoy it, but know it will pass. Nothing lasts forever except the Self." },
      { heading: "You Are Not the Doer", text: "Isha Upanishad 1 — 'Everything in the universe belongs to the Lord. See the Self in all and do not claim ownership.' Stop trying to control everything. Life flows through you. You are not the doer — you are the instrument. Relax. Surrender. Let life live through you." },
      { heading: "The Peace You Seek Is Within", text: "Katha Upanishad 2.2.1 — 'The Self is hidden in the heart of every being, subtler than the subtlest.' You have been searching outside for happiness — in people, things, achievements. But what you seek is inside you. Turn inward. The peace you are chasing has been waiting for you all along." },
      { heading: "You Are Pure Awareness", text: "Mandukya Upanishad 7 — 'The fourth state (Turiya) is pure consciousness, beyond waking, dreaming, and sleep.' At the end of the day, you are not your job, your relationships, or your body. You are pure awareness. Rest in that. This realization is the ultimate peace." },
      { heading: "The Three States of Consciousness", text: "Mandukya Upanishad 3-6 — 'There are three states: waking, dreaming, and deep sleep. Beyond all three is Turiya — pure consciousness.' In waking, you experience the outside world. In dreaming, you experience your inner world. In deep sleep, you experience stillness. But you are none of these. You are the one who WITNESSES all three. That witness is you." },
      { heading: "The Five Sheaths of the Self", text: "Taittiriya Upanishad 2.1-5 — 'The Self is hidden within five layers: the physical body, the energy body, the mind, the intellect, and the bliss body.' You are not just your physical body. Beneath it is energy. Beneath energy is mind. Beneath mind is wisdom. And at the core is pure bliss. Your true self is peace itself, layer by layer by layer." },
      { heading: "Neti Neti — Not This, Not This", text: "Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 2.3.6 — 'The Self is described as Neti Neti — not this, not this. It cannot be defined. It can only be pointed to.' You cannot say 'the Self is this.' Because the Self is beyond every definition. Are you the body? Neti — not this. Are you the mind? Neti — not this. Are you your thoughts? Neti. Keep removing. What remains is the truth." },
      { heading: "The Universe Lives Inside You", text: "Chandogya Upanishad 3.12.6 — 'Everything in the universe is within you, as vast as the infinite.' Mountains, rivers, stars, gods — all are within. You are not a small person in a big world. You are a vast universe in a small body. Feel your immensity." },
      { heading: "The Chariot of the Body", text: "Katha Upanishad 1.3.3-4 — 'The body is the chariot. The senses are the horses. The mind is the reins. The intellect is the charioteer. The Self is the passenger.' You are not the chariot. You are not the horses. You are not even the charioteer. You are the passenger — the one who simply watches the ride. Relax into the passenger seat. The charioteer knows the way." },
      { heading: "Two Birds on the Same Tree", text: "Mundaka Upanishad 3.1.1-2 — 'Two birds sit on the same tree. One eats the fruit. The other watches silently.' One bird is your everyday self — busy, tasting, enjoying, suffering. The other bird is your true self — watching, silent, peaceful. Both sit in the same body. Most people live as the first bird. But peace comes when you remember: you are also the second bird." },
      { heading: "Let Go of Needing Things to Be Different", text: "Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 4.4.6 — 'When there is duality, one fears the other. But when the Self alone is seen, there is no fear.' You cannot control what happens. But you can control your response. When you stop needing things to go a certain way, you become free. Peace is letting go." },
      { heading: "You Are the Silent Witness", text: "Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.16 — 'The Self is the inner witness, unseen yet seeing, unheard yet hearing.' There is a part of you that never changes. It watches thoughts come and go. It watches emotions rise and fall. Connect with this witness. It is your true self, untouched by time." },
      { heading: "The Story of Nachiketa: Facing Death", text: "Katha Upanishad 1.1.1-29 — 'Nachiketa, a young boy, asked Death himself: what happens after death? Death replied: the Self is never born and never dies.' Nachiketa was not afraid to ask the biggest questions. He faced Death and asked for wisdom. Most of us are afraid of death, of loss, of change. But the Upanishads say: there is nothing to fear. The Self is immortal." },
      { heading: "The Self Is Never Born, Never Dies", text: "Katha Upanishad 1.2.18-19 — 'The Self is not born, nor does it die. It does not come from anywhere. It is unborn, eternal, ever-existing.' Your body will age and die. Your thoughts will come and go. Your emotions will rise and fall. But the Self — the pure awareness within you — never changes. It was there before you were born. It will be there after. You are eternal." },
      { heading: "Don't Mistake the Finger for the Moon", text: "Kena Upanishad 1.3 — 'The truth cannot be captured by words. Words only point to it.' Do not mistake the finger pointing at the moon for the moon itself. Scripture points to truth, but it is not truth. Go beyond concepts. Experience directly. The taste of sweetness is not the word 'sweet.'" },
      { heading: "Who Is the Knower?", text: "Kena Upanishad 1.1-2 — 'What is it that makes the mind think? What is it that makes the eyes see? What is it that makes the ears hear?' The Upanishads ask you to look behind your own experience. Who is seeing through your eyes right now? Who is hearing through your ears? Before you think, who decides to think? That question itself leads you to peace." },
      { heading: "Die Before You Die", text: "Katha Upanishad 2.3.14 — 'When the wise let go of their desires and attachments, they become immortal.' Die before you die, so that when you die, you do not die. This means: let go of your ego, your attachments, your false identities while you are still alive. Only then do you know true freedom." },
      { heading: "The World Is a Mirror of Your Mind", text: "Chandogya Upanishad 8.3.4 — 'As is the mind, so is the world.' How you see the world is how you see yourself. If you see fault everywhere, look within. If you see beauty everywhere, you have found peace within. The world is a mirror — clean the mirror, and the reflection changes." },
      { heading: "The Honey of All Existence", text: "Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 2.5.1 — 'The honey doctrine: all beings are the honey of the Self. The Self is the honey of all beings.' Everything in existence is sweet when you realize it is made of the same substance as you. The trees, the stars, the strangers on the street — they are all made of the same awareness. When you taste this unity, peace is not something you find. It is something you are." },
      { heading: "You Were Never Bound", text: "Chandogya Upanishad 6.14.2 — 'The one who knows the Self is free. Always. From the beginning.' You are not trying to become free. You are already free. You have just forgotten. Like a bird that does not know it can fly. Open your wings. You have always been free. You only need to remember." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 10,
    title: "Courage",
    scripture: "Mahabharata",
     subtitle: "Lessons in courage from the great war of the Mahabharata.",
    source: "Explore Mahabharata",
    bg: "#6B3030",
    accent: "#E09090",
    emoji: "🔱",
    image: BOOK_IMAGES[10] || null,
    sampleVerse: "Do not yield to weakness, Arjuna. Shake off your faint-hearted heart and arise. — Bhagavad Gita 2.3",
    pages: [
      { heading: "Courage Is Not the Absence of Fear", text: "Bhagavad Gita 2.3 — 'Do not yield to weakness, Arjuna. This does not become you. Shake off your faint heart and arise.' Courage is not being fearless. Arjuna was terrified before the battle. Krishna did not say 'don't be afraid.' He said: feel the fear, get up anyway, and do what needs to be done." },
      { heading: "Stand Up for What Is Right, Even Alone", text: "Bhagavad Gita 2.31 — 'Do your duty without hesitation. For a warrior, there is nothing better than a righteous battle.' Sometimes you have to stand alone. When you know something is right, don't back down. Even if everyone disagrees. Even if it is hard. Your integrity is worth more than approval." },
      { heading: "The Biggest Battle Is Inside You", text: "Bhagavad Gita 6.5 — 'Lift yourself up with your own effort. Do not let yourself sink. You are your own best friend or your own worst enemy.' Fear, doubt, laziness, self-pity — these are your real enemies. Every time you choose courage over comfort, you win a small battle. Over time, you become unstoppable." },
      { heading: "You Are Stronger Than You Know", text: "Bhagavad Gita 18.59 — 'The force of your own nature will drive you to fight. What you refuse out of fear, you will do anyway.' You have no idea how strong you are. When life pushes you, you discover reserves of strength you didn't know you had. Hard times do not create strength. They reveal it." },
      { heading: "One Step at a Time Wins the War", text: "Bhagavad Gita 2.47 — 'Focus on your action, not on the result. Do your duty without worrying about the outcome.' When something feels overwhelming, don't think about the whole mountain. Just take one step. Then another. Courage is not one big heroic act. It is a thousand small acts of showing up." },
      { heading: "Speak Your Truth Without Fear", text: "Bhagavad Gita 18.65 — 'Fix your mind on Me, give your heart to Me, and you will overcome all difficulties.' It takes courage to say what you really feel. To set boundaries. To say no. But your truth matters. Don't shrink yourself to make others comfortable. The world needs your authentic voice." },
      { heading: "Get Back Up Every Single Time", text: "Bhagavad Gita 2.14 — 'Pleasure and pain come and go like the seasons. Learn to bear them with patience.' Falling is not failure. Staying down is failure. Every time you fall and get back up, you become stronger. Life will knock you down — that is guaranteed. What matters is how many times you get back up." },
      { heading: "Bhishma's Vow: Unbreakable Commitment", text: "Mahabharata, Adi Parva — 'Bhishma, the son of Ganga, took a vow of lifelong celibacy so his father could marry the woman he loved. He gave up the throne, marriage, and fatherhood — for his father's happiness.' Bhishma's courage was in sacrifice. He gave up everything he could have had. True courage is not just fighting. It is giving up what you want for what is right. His word was so strong that even Death respected it." },
      { heading: "Draupadi's Courage: Standing Alone", text: "Mahabharata, Sabha Parva — 'When Draupadi was dragged into the court by Dushasana, everyone sat silent. No one spoke for her. But she did not break. She questioned the court's dharma. She refused to be silent.' One woman against an entire court. Kings, warriors, elders — all sat watching. But Draupadi did not beg. She demanded justice. She questioned the men who called themselves righteous. Courage is not having power. It is speaking truth when everyone else is silent." },
      { heading: "Abhimanyu: The Courage of Youth", text: "Mahabharata, Drona Parva — 'Abhimanyu, just 16 years old, broke through the Chakravyuha formation knowing he would not return. Seven great warriors attacked him at once. He fought them all alone.' Abhimanyu knew how to enter the formation but not how to exit. Yet he entered anyway. He knew he might die. But he also knew his army needed him. Sometimes courage means going in even when you don't know the way out." },
      { heading: "Karna: Generosity in the Face of Suffering", text: "Mahabharata, Udyoga Parva — 'Karna was cursed, abandoned, and humiliated all his life. Yet when he was dying, Indra came disguised as a beggar and asked for his divine armor. Karna cut it from his body and gave it away — even knowing Indra's daughter had killed his son.' Karna's life was full of injustice. Yet he never stopped giving. When people asked for anything, he gave it — even knowing it would cost him his life. True courage is being generous even when life has been cruel to you." },
      { heading: "You Were Born for This Moment", text: "Bhagavad Gita 4.7 — 'Whenever dharma declines and adharma rises, I manifest Myself to protect the good and restore balance.' The universe has placed you exactly where you need to be. Whatever battle you are facing right now, you have the strength to face it. Rise. Fight. You are ready." },
      { heading: "True Courage Protects the Weak", text: "Bhagavad Gita 1.33-34 — 'Arjuna saw his teachers, fathers, and sons standing before him, and his heart broke.' True courage is not about winning. It is about protecting those who cannot protect themselves. Stand up for the weak. Speak for the voiceless. That is what Arjuna fought for." },
      { heading: "Do Not Run From Your Duty", text: "Bhagavad Gita 2.35 — 'People will speak of your dishonor forever. For a warrior, that is worse than death.' Avoiding conflict does not make you peaceful. It makes you a doormat. Sometimes you must fight for what is right. Not with violence, but with conviction. Stand your ground." },
      { heading: "Eklavya: The Courage to Keep Learning", text: "Mahabharata, Adi Parva — 'Eklavya, a tribal boy, was rejected by Dronacharya because of his caste. Undeterred, he made a clay statue of Drona and taught himself. He became the greatest archer of his time — through pure dedication.' Eklavya did not let rejection stop him. He did not need permission to learn. When the teacher refused to teach, he made his own teacher. Courage is not waiting for someone to give you a chance. It is creating your own chance." },
      { heading: "Vidura's Wisdom: The Courage to Speak Truth to Power", text: "Mahabharata, Udyoga Parva — 'Vidura, though born a servant, was the wisest of all. He alone told Dhritarashtra the truth when everyone else flattered him.' Vidura had nothing — no kingdom, no army, no position. But he had wisdom and truth. He was not afraid to tell the king what no one else would say. True courage is speaking truth to power, even when it costs you everything." },
      { heading: "Arjuna's Penance: The Courage to Struggle", text: "Mahabharata, Aranya Parva — 'Arjuna went to the Himalayas to obtain divine weapons. He stood on one leg, arms up, for days, meditating on Shiva. He went through unimaginable hardship for his goal.' Arjuna did not just fight on the battlefield. He fought against his own body, his own pain, his own limits. He endured cold, hunger, and exhaustion. Courage is often not glamorous. It is standing on one leg in the cold when no one is watching." },
      { heading: "Win the Inner War First", text: "Bhagavad Gita 6.6 — 'If you control your mind, it becomes your best friend. If you do not, it becomes your worst enemy.' The Mahabharata is not just a story about a war outside. It is about the war inside you. Your selfishness versus your generosity. Your fear versus your courage. Win the inner war first." },
      { heading: "Krishna's Counsel: Act Without Attachment", text: "Bhagavad Gita 2.38 — 'Treat pleasure and pain, gain and loss, victory and defeat as the same. Then fight. You will not incur sin.' Krishna's advice is revolutionary. Don't fight because you are attached to winning. Fight because it is the right thing to do. When you let go of the outcome, you become unstoppable. Fear comes from attachment. Courage comes from detachment." },
      { heading: "The Courage to Forgive", text: "Mahabharata, Stri Parva — 'After the war, Gandhari cursed Krishna for allowing the destruction. Yudhishthira, who lost all his sons, still ruled with compassion and forgiveness.' Yudhishthira had every reason to be bitter. He lost his kingdom, his peace, and his children. Yet he did not become cruel. He forgave. Sometimes the bravest thing is not fighting. It is forgiving after being wronged." },
      { heading: "You Are Not Alone — Trust Your Allies", text: "Bhagavad Gita 2.7 — 'I am confused about my duty. I ask You to guide me. I am Your student. Teach me.' Arjuna had Krishna. You too have allies — friends, family, mentors. You do not have to fight alone. Reach out. Ask for help. True courage is also knowing when to lean on others." },
      { heading: "The Courage to Surrender", text: "Bhagavad Gita 18.66 — 'Give up all your duties and surrender to Me. I will free you from all sins. Do not worry.' Sometimes the most courageous thing is not fighting harder. It is surrendering. Let go of control. Trust something greater than yourself. Arjuna had to fight, but he also had to surrender. Effort and surrender go together. Courage is knowing when to do each." },
      { heading: "Your Word Is Your Bond", text: "Mahabharata, Udyoga Parva — 'Bhishma's vow was unbreakable. Even facing death, he did not break his word.' In the Mahabharata, keeping one's word was sacred. Once given, it could not be broken. Be a person of your word. When you say you will do something, do it. Your word is your bond." },
      { heading: "Fight From Dharma, Not From Anger", text: "Bhagavad Gita 2.48 — 'Be steady in yoga. Do your duty without attachment to success or failure. This balance is yoga.' Do not fight because you are angry. Fight because it is your dharma. Anger clouds judgment. Dharma gives clarity. Act from principle, not from emotion. That is the warrior's way." },
      { heading: "Savitri's Love: Courage Beyond Death", text: "Mahabharata, Vana Parva — 'Savitri married Satyavan knowing he would die in a year. When Yama came to take her husband, she followed Death itself and argued until he returned her husband's life.' Savitri did not accept fate. She faced Death himself and won through love and wisdom. She did not fight with weapons. She fought with words and presence. Courage is not always about battles. Sometimes it is about refusing to give up on someone you love." },
      { heading: "Dharma Always Wins in the End", text: "Bhagavad Gita 4.8 — 'I come age after age to protect the righteous and destroy the wicked.' In the end, dharma always wins. It may take time. The path may be hard. But truth and righteousness prevail. Have faith. Do the right thing. Victory will follow." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 11,
    title: "Simplicity & Ego",
    scripture: "Kabirdas",
    subtitle: "Kabir's dohas on cutting the ego and living simply.",
    source: "Explore Kabirdas",
    bg: "#8B6B3A",
    accent: "#F0D68A",
    emoji: "🪶",
    image: BOOK_IMAGES[11] || null,
    sampleVerse: "Bada hua toh kya hua, jaise ped khajoor. Panthi ko chaya nahi, phal lage atidoor. — Kabir",
    pages: [
      { heading: "The Tallest Tree Bears No Fruit for You", text: "Kabir says: 'Bada hua toh kya hua, jaise ped khajoor. Panthi ko chaya nahi, phal lage atidoor.' What good is being tall if you cast no shade? The ego makes you stand above others — but no one finds rest under you. True greatness is not how high you stand, but how many you shelter." },
      { heading: "You Are Not the Body, You Are Not the Mind", text: "Kabir says: 'Jo main so main nahi, main toh wohi jo Rama se Rama hai.' The 'I' you are so protective of — it is not real. Strip away the ego, and what remains is the divine. Your anger, your pride, your hurt feelings — all belong to the false self. Let them go." },
      { heading: "Drop the 'I' and Find Peace", text: "Kabir says: 'Jab main tha tab Hari nahi, ab Hari hain main nahi.' When the ego was, God was not. Now that God is, the ego is not. The two cannot coexist. Every time you say 'I did this,' 'I suffered this,' you strengthen the wall between you and peace. Drop the 'I' and see how light you feel." },
      { heading: "Who Do You Think You Are?", text: "Kabir says: 'Mala pherat jug gaya, gaya na man ka pher. Kar ka manka dasi, kar hi manka pher.' You have spent years counting beads, but your mind keeps spinning. All your rituals mean nothing if the ego still sits on the throne. True prayer is not in the hands — it is in letting go of who you think you are." },
      { heading: "Silence the Ego, Hear the Truth", text: "Kabir says: 'Kasturi kundal base, mrig dhundhe ban mahi.' The musk is inside the deer, but it runs through the forest looking for it. You search for peace in places, people, and possessions. But peace is inside you — buried under the noise of the ego. Be still. Listen inward." },
      { heading: "Your Pride Is a Wall", text: "Kabir says: 'Pothi padh padh kar mua, pandit bhaya na koy. Dhai akshar prem ka, padhe so pandit hoy.' You can read every scripture and become a scholar. But without love, you know nothing. The ego loves knowledge — it uses it to feel superior. But wisdom without humility is just a bigger cage. Drop the pride of knowing. Just love." },
      { heading: "What You Cling to, You Lose", text: "Kabir says: 'Chinta aisi kathin hai, jyon chakki ki dhar. Tis upar jo chadh gaya, pav na pawe paar.' Worry is like the millstone — it keeps turning and grinding you down. The ego clings to outcomes, to people, to identity. And the clinging is the very thing that crushes you. Release your grip. Let life flow." },
      { heading: "The Wiser You Are, the Quieter You Become", text: "Kabir says: 'Nindak niyare rakhiye, aangan kuti chhay. Bin sabun pani, malin jo so dhoy.' Keep your critic close — they clean your ego without soap or water. Kabir says a true seeker welcomes criticism because it polishes the soul. If you get defensive when corrected, your ego is still in charge. Be grateful for those who show you your edges." },
      { heading: "Simplicity Is Not Poverty, It Is Freedom", text: "Kabir says: 'Jahan chah tahan rah nahi, jahan rah tahan chah nahi.' Where there is desire, there is no peace. Where there is peace, there is no desire. You think more will make you happy — more money, more things, more respect. But each addition is another chain. Simplicity is not about having less. It is about needing less." },
      { heading: "Stop Performing for the World", text: "Kabir says: 'Aisi bani boliyen, man ka paap khoti. Gagan pataal ek kar, aap khade sain soti.' You speak sweet words while your mind is full of rot. You pretend to be humble while the ego swells. Kabir sees through the mask. God sees through the mask. The only one you are fooling is yourself. Be real. Be raw. Be true." },
      { heading: "You Came Alone, You Will Leave Alone", text: "Kabir says: 'Aavat aap akele, jaawe aap akele. Koi kisi ka nahi, sab hai budhau ke mele.' You came alone, you will go alone. No one is yours — this whole world is a fair you are passing through. The ego makes you cling — to your children, your reputation, your body. But all of it will be left behind. Why carry what you cannot keep?" },
      { heading: "The River Flows, the Fool Stands Still", text: "Kabir says: 'Nadiya kinare sookhi, mrig machhli jal jay. Apani aankh na dhari, to bhed na jani jay.' The river dries up, the fish and deer die. But the fool stands by the dry bed, waiting for water that will not come. The ego clings to old ways, old identities, old stories. But life moves. Let the old you die. Flow with the river." },
      { heading: "When You Know You Don't Know, You Begin to Know", text: "Kabir says: 'Jo main kahu so main nahi, jo main nahi so main. Yaha mai padha bujha nahi, to kahe ka abhiman?' Whatever I say I am, I am not. Whatever I say I am not, I am. Kabir plays with identity. The moment you claim to know, you have stopped learning. The moment you say 'I am wise,' the ego has taken over. Stay a beginner. Stay empty." },
      { heading: "Do Not Boast of Your Good Deeds", text: "Kabir says: 'Jab main tha tab Hari nahi, ab Hari hain main nahi. Sab jag dekhe ek kar, nahi dekhe to kya?' When the ego was active, God was hidden. Every good deed done with ego is just another brick in your wall of pride. Give without claiming. Help without announcing. The left hand should not know what the right hand gives." },
      { heading: "Your Identity Is Your Cage", text: "Kabir says: 'Kaal kare so aaj kar, aaj kare so ab. Pal mein pralay hoga, bahuri karega kab?' Time is running. Death does not wait. Yet you waste your days defending your identity — your name, your status, your story. All of it will dissolve in a moment. Why spend your precious hours polishing a cage?" },
      { heading: "The One Who Knows, Stays Silent", text: "Kabir says: 'Jaanat jo hai so kahi nahi, kahat jo hai so jaan nahi. Aisa samajh le bhai, sach ke aage sab jhooth.' The one who knows, does not speak. The one who speaks, does not know. Truth is not something you preach — it is something you live. A simple life, a quiet heart, a humble presence — that is the real teaching." },
      { heading: "You Are Not the Potter, You Are the Clay", text: "Kabir says: 'Kumhar se jo bigde, to ghade ki kya kahun? Para jo hath tumhare, to tum kya karo?' If the potter makes a mistake, do you blame the pot? Kabir reminds you: you are not in control. You are the clay, not the potter. The ego wants to be the one shaping everything. But surrender is realizing you are being shaped. Trust the hands that hold you." },
      { heading: "Jealousy Is the Ego's Fear", text: "Kabir says: 'Dheere dheere hari bhajan karo, dheere dheere prem karo. Prem karna mushkil hai, dheere dheere karo.' Love and devotion cannot be rushed. Jealousy comes when you compare — and comparison is the ego's favorite game. Someone else's success is not your failure. Run your own race at your own pace. Slow and steady, with a quiet heart." },
      { heading: "The Mirror Does Not Lie", text: "Kabir says: 'Aisi aankh na dekhiye, jo kare darpan saath. Darpan apna jhoot hai, jo dekhe se hath.' Do not look for truth in a mirror — the image you see is not you. Your face will age. Your body will change. That is not who you are. The ego identifies with the reflection, but you are the one seeing the reflection. Look behind the eyes. That is the real you." },
      { heading: "Live Like the Lotus", text: "Kabir says: 'Nadiya ke kinare, kya kare kumhila? Jal mein rahe kamal, kya kare pani ka?' The lotus lives in water, yet the water does not touch it. Kabir says: live in the world, but not of it. Have possessions but do not be possessed by them. Have relationships but do not let them own you. Be in the world like the lotus — rooted in mud, but blooming untouched." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 12,
    title: "Overthinking",
    scripture: "Adi Shankaracharya",
    subtitle: "Shankara's advaita wisdom to silence the restless mind.",
    source: "Explore Adi Shankaracharya",
    bg: "#4A3A5A",
    accent: "#C0A8E8",
    emoji: "🧠",
    image: BOOK_IMAGES[12] || null,
    sampleVerse: "Brahma Satyam Jagan Mithya — Brahman alone is real, the world is an appearance. — Adi Shankaracharya",
    pages: [
      { heading: "The World You Worry About Is a Dream", text: "Shankara's famous declaration: 'Brahma Satyam Jagan Mithya.' Only the Self is real. The world you overthink about — the conversations, the judgments, the future — it is a passing appearance like a dream. When you know this deep in your bones, worry loses its power. How can a dream hurt you when you know it is a dream?" },
      { heading: "You Are Not Your Thoughts", text: "Shankara says in Atma Bodha: 'The Self is the witness of the mind and its thoughts. It is distinct from them, like a lamp is distinct from the objects it illuminates.' Your thoughts are objects passing through awareness. You are not the thoughts. You are the awareness behind them. Watch them like clouds. They come, they go. You remain." },
      { heading: "Stop Feeding the Mind's Stories", text: "Shankara says: 'The mind creates the world of names and forms. When the mind is still, the world dissolves.' Overthinking is just the mind telling itself stories. 'What if they are angry at me?' 'What if I fail?' These are stories. Nothing more. Your mind has convinced you they are real. But you have a choice: stop feeding the story. Let it starve." },
      { heading: "The Mind Creates the Problem", text: "Shankara says: 'There is no bondage. There is only ignorance. And ignorance is only the lack of self-knowledge.' You think your problems are real. But Shankara says: the only real problem is forgetting who you are. Overthinking about money, relationships, health — all symptoms of the same root: you have forgotten the peace that is your true nature. Remember that, and the rest dissolves." },
      { heading: "You Search Outside for What Is Inside", text: "Shankara says in Vivekachudamani: 'The wise one realizes the Self within, not by looking outward but by turning inward.' You overthink because you look outside for answers. 'Did I do enough?' 'What do they think of me?' All outward questions. But the answer to every question is inside you. Stop searching. Turn inward. Sit still. Listen." },
      { heading: "Attachment Is the Root of All Mental Suffering", text: "Shankara says: 'Attachment to the body and the world is the cause of all suffering. Freedom lies in realizing you are neither.' You are overthinking about someone or something because you are attached. You want things to go a certain way. You want people to act a certain way. That wanting is the root of the pain. Let go of how things 'should' be, and the mind settles." },
      { heading: "The Rope and the Snake: A Parable for Overthinkers", text: "Shankara's famous analogy: in dim light, you see a rope and mistake it for a snake. Your heart races. You panic. But when someone shines a light, you see it is just a rope. The snake was never real — only your misunderstanding caused the fear. Overthinking is the same. The problem you are obsessing over is the snake. The truth, when seen clearly, is the rope. Shine the light of awareness, and the fear dissolves." },
      { heading: "You Are the Silence Between Thoughts", text: "Shankara says: 'The Self is pure consciousness, beyond the mind, beyond words, beyond thought.' Between two thoughts, there is a gap. That gap is you. Not the thoughts. The silence. The more you rest in that gap, the less the thoughts trouble you. You are not the noisy mind. You are the silent space in which the noise appears." },
      { heading: "Stop Identifying With Your Worries", text: "Shankara says: 'The identification of the Self with the not-Self is the cause of bondage.' You say 'I am anxious,' 'I am worried,' 'I am stressed.' But these are states passing through, not who you are. You are not anxiety. You are not worry. You are the one noticing the anxiety and worry. Step back from the identification and watch. The watcher is always at peace." },
      { heading: "Renounce the Need to Control", text: "Shankara says: 'Renunciation is not giving up the world. It is giving up the attachment to the world.' You cannot control outcomes. You cannot control other people. Overthinking is the attempt to control the uncontrollable with your mind. Renounce that illusion of control. Do your best. Let the rest go. The peace you seek comes from surrender, not control." },
      { heading: "The Present Moment Is All There Is", text: "Shankara says: 'Time, space, and causation are appearances in the one consciousness. They have no independent reality.' Past and future are mental constructs. The past is a memory happening now. The future is an imagination happening now. Overthinking is living in these mental constructions. Come back to now. Only this moment is real. Only this moment is alive." },
      { heading: "Wisdom Cuts Through the Knot of Doubt", text: "Shankara says: 'The sword of knowledge cuts the knot of doubt in the heart.' Overthinking is a knot — a tangle of 'what ifs' and 'maybes.' You cannot untie it by thinking more. You cut through it with wisdom. And wisdom is not more thinking. Wisdom is seeing clearly that the problem is only in your mind. One moment of clear seeing can end years of overthinking." },
      { heading: "You Are Already Free, You Just Don't Know It", text: "Shankara says: 'You are already free. You just think you are bound. Know the truth and be free.' A man dreaming he is a prisoner wakes up and laughs. You are that man. You think you are trapped in your thoughts, your problems, your life. But you are already free. You just need to wake up. The freedom is not something to achieve. It is something to remember." },
      { heading: "When Thoughts Come, Let Them Pass", text: "Shankara says: 'Let thoughts come and go. Do not welcome them, do not resist them. Just watch.' The mind is like a river. Thoughts flow endlessly. Fighting the flow tires you. Going with the flow drowns you. But sitting on the bank and watching — that is freedom. Be the bank, not the river. Watch your thoughts pass without getting caught in them." },
      { heading: "Overthinking Is a Form of Self-Doubt", text: "Shankara says in Atma Bodha: 'Ignorance makes you see the Self as separate and weak. Knowledge reveals it as one and infinite.' Every anxious thought is a form of forgetting. You are the infinite consciousness. The overthinking mind says 'I am small, I am vulnerable, I need to control everything.' That is ignorance speaking. Remember your true nature — vast, free, untouched — and the small worries fall away." },
      { heading: "Do Not Believe Everything Your Mind Tells You", text: "Shankara says: 'Just as the same moon appears to move when clouds move, the Self appears to be troubled when the mind is restless.' Your mind tells you stories. 'Something bad will happen.' 'They don't like you.' 'You are not good enough.' These are clouds passing across the moon. They do not touch the moon. Do not believe every thought. Not every thought is true." },
      { heading: "Knowing One Thing, You Know Everything", text: "Shankara says: 'By knowing the Self, everything else is known. The Self is the source of all knowledge.' You spend so much energy trying to figure everything out — your career, your relationships, your future. But Shankara says: know one thing. Know yourself. When you know who you truly are, every question finds its answer. Not because you have more information, but because you are no longer lost." },
      { heading: "Peace Is Your True Nature", text: "Shankara says: 'The Self is peace itself. It is not something you achieve. It is something you uncover.' But Shankara says: there will always be another problem. Do not postpone your peace. Find it now, in the middle of the mess. The perfect moment will never come. This moment is all you have." },
    ],
  },
];

